@Deleted User Before we proceed, I must ensure you understand your rights in this matter:

1. You have the right to remain silent. This means you do not have to speak or provide any information that could incriminate you.

2. You also have the right to have an attorney present during any questioning or legal proceedings. If you cannot afford an attorney, one will be appointed for you at no cost.

3. You have the right to a fair and public trial, where evidence will be presented, and witnesses can be called to testify on your behalf.

4. Furthermore, you have the right to confront witnesses against you, meaning you can question them in court.

5. Finally, you have the right to appeal any conviction or sentence imposed upon you.
meowiitten 2025-03-14 03:50 p.m.
This is Case Number CR-0083-25 before the Mayflower District Court in the County of Clark: State of Mayflower v. tactical_pancakes. The information is as follows:

COUNT ONE
SECOND-DEGREE MURDER (1 M.S.C. 2102) - FELONY
On or about March 10, 2025, the defendant did respond to an alleged call for distress
which was later declared as complete before his arrival. The defendant, upon his arrival, exited
his vehicle with a submachine gun and fired approximately eight bullets on a uniformed police
officer who had his weapon secured in a holster while merely standing idly. The defendant did
intentionally fire the bullets from his submachine gun with the clear purpose being to inflict
serious bodily injury or death upon the victim. This offense occurred on the highway near the
tunnel within approximately two miles of Mersea which is within the geographical boundaries of
the State of Mayflower.

COUNT ONE
FELONY MISCONDUCT (1 M.S.C. 1302) - FELONY
On or about March 10, 2025, the defendant did respond to an alleged call for distress
which was later declared as complete before his arrival. The defendant, upon his arrival, exited his vehicle with a submachine gun and fired approximately eight bullets on a uniformed police officer who had his weapon secured in a holster while merely standing idly. The defendant did not use force consistent with 4 M.S.C. 5 1307 and is therefore liable to be charged under 4 M.S.C. 5 2601(c) which authorizes this charged offense for Felony Misconduct.

Signed March 12, 2025.

PAPERLESS ORDER: It is ORDERED AND ADJUDGED that the Court confirms the State's obligation to disclose to the defendant all exculpatory evidencenamely, evidence that favors the defendant or casts doubt on the State's caseas required by the principles established in Brady v. Maryland, 373 U.S. 83 (1963) and its progeny. The State is hereby ORDERED to fulfill this obligation. The State has a duty to disclose any evidence that negates the defendant's guilt, affects the credibility of a witness, or could potentially reduce a sentence. The defendant is entitled to this information without needing to make a request. Failure to disclose exculpatory evidence in a timely manner may result in consequences, including, but not limited to, exclusion of evidence, dismissal of the information, contempt proceedings, disciplinary action, or sanctions by the Court. meowiitten 2025-03-25 05:54 p.m.
Okay, so I'm not even going to ask for a statement of facts; I am going to reject this plea agreement as it does not serve the interests of justice nor the public interest.[1] The defendant is charged with Second-Degree Murder and Felony Misconductboth serious feloniescarrying a maximum sentence of 100 minutes all together, yet this plea agreement reduces the charges to misdemeanors with only 10 minutes of incarceration. Given that I am supposed to accept the allegations in the information as true when reviewing a plea agreement, this is a grossly disproportionate reduction in charges given the severity of the alleged conduct and I cannot accept it.

You can come back with a plea agreement that more accurately reflects the gravity of the offenses alleged, but I will not approve a deal that so drastically minimizes the defendants culpability.

@Evexom @Deleted User @dero @walter!

[1] Several circuit courts have approved consideration of the public interest in accepting or rejecting a plea agreement. The Ninth Circuit in particular has stated, "a district court properly exercises its discretion when it rejects a plea agreement calling for a sentence the court believes is too lenient or otherwise not in the public interest in light of the factual circumstances specific to the case." In re Morgan, 506 F.3d 705, 712 (9th Cir. 2007) (internal quotations omitted). The First Circuit has stated as a reason why the court must have discretion whether or not to accept a plea "that a conviction affects more than the court and the defendant; the public is involved." United States v. Bednarski, 445 F.2d 364, 366 (1st Cir. 1971).

meowiitten 2025-03-30 06:14 p.m.
Well, I'm questioning your rationale if the only stated reason for downgrading from Second-Degree Murder to Voluntary Manslaughter is to avoid trial. Both versions of the information allege that the defendant intentionally fired the weapon with the purpose of causing death or serious injury. Theres no factual softening of the defendants mindset, other than the tacked-on line about a sudden quarrel.

Voluntary manslaughter generally applies when theres a mitigating factor like a sudden provocation (e.g. a fist-fight or heated argument) that would cause a reasonable person to lose self-control. But theres nothing in either version that shows thatespecially since the officer was merely standing idly with a holstered weapon. That doesn't scream "mutual quarrel." If you believe you can prove intent to killand the defendant is going to plead to it in this amended versionwhy reduce the charge?

Also, as for Count Two, the factual allegations stay the same, it's just the legal classification that is lowered. The alleged conduct still fits a Felony Misconduct charge; it even still says "felony misconduct" at the end of the amended count.
